			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">if we need to permit the use of chrome or chrome-extension, we should be explicit 
about it.

standard security practice is to avoid blacklists, since new stuff automatically 
passes blacklist checks, and new schemes should be carefully considered before being 
allowed -- the cost incorrectly allowing something through is a security failure, 
which is deemed higher than the cost of not immediately working for a new protocol 
scheme when that scheme is not dangerous.
